\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Discussion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not possible to establish a common method for whole text visualizations.
 As expected, all the cases present an axis that represents the whole text.
 In all the cases except in two, the text line is represented by a horizontal
 or a vertical line.
 The exceptions represent the text line as a circle (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:1Novel-Views:-Les-1"

\end_inset

) and as an iconification of a text in a page, (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:7Texty,-a-visualization"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since whole text visualization always includes an abstraction of the text
 that we call text line, a question arises: which part of the text is physically
 present in the reviewed whole text visualizations? It is surprising that
 most of the cases, nine out of fifteen, did not show a single word (cases:
 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 15).
 Four cases show a small number of words (1, 2, 12, 13).
 Only two cases show all the text, cases 3 and 14.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most common pattern is to show the occurrence of some feature - perhaps
 term, or topic, or cross-reference, or character - within the text as a
 whole (all the cases except 3, 12, 13 and 15).
 Except in Wattenberg's arc diagrams, occurrence is represented by same
 color.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is interesting to observe how some cases represent very similar data in
 very different ways.
 This is the case of History Flow by ViÃ©gas and Wattenberg (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:10History-Flow-by"

\end_inset

) and Favoured Traces by Fry (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:6On-the-Origin"

\end_inset

): both show the same thing - document version history by document section
 - but the first is spatialized and the second animated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also see similarities between Texty (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:7Texty,-a-visualization"

\end_inset

), and TileBars (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:15TileBars:-Visualization-of"

\end_inset

).
 Here Texty uses the same technique as TileBars, highlighting some words
 of the text inside a rectangular figure that represents the whole text.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also observe cases that are opposite or complementary one to another,
 like Wattenberg's Arc diagram (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:14Arc-diagram-Wattenberg"

\end_inset

), which shows repetition, and Hurst's novelty visualization (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:5Visualizing-Lexical-Novelty"

\end_inset

), which shows only new strings, not repetitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Literature and other complex texts, like political speeches (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:4State-of-the"

\end_inset

) or the bible (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:8Bible-Cross-References-by"

\end_inset

) dominate the kind of corpora of this category (ten cases).
 In our opinion, this is surprising because these texts are complex, sometimes
 with a high level of abstraction and little formal structure.
 In our opinion, in order to introduce or test a new tool, it is a good
 idea to work with more structured and 
\shape italic
easier
\shape default
