\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Sequential visualization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found sixteen cases out of twenty-three in single text visualization
 in which the visualization keeps a similar sequence as the original text
 does.
 Seven of the sixteen visualize the sequence using a discourse structure,
 mainly chapters.
 The rest, nine cases use syntactic elements to represent the original sequence
 of the text, mainly words.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is remarkable that only one case (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:22Document-Arc-Diagrams"

\end_inset

) belonging to part text visualization follows the original text sequence.
 And, at the same time, all the whole text visualization cases are also
 sequential.
 It seems that sequentiality is intrinsic to whole text visualization.
 Whole text visualizations do not literally represent every word of the
 text, but a graphical metaphor of the whole text: a text line.
 This text line can represent a discourse structure of the text or a syntactic
 one, in any case, graphically there is a line or an area that represents
 the length of the text.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sequentiality in visualization allows the reader to go back and forward
 between the visualization as in the text.
 In the case of a long text, a book (nine out of sixteen cases) the visualizatio
n can act as a map or a guide to the text.
\end_layout

