\begin_layout Standard
Regarding the literature review we are sure that we have not covered all
 the existing ideas related to text visualization.
 Certainly because data and text visualization is a relatively new field
 there is no single consolidated list of dedicated publications and sources.
 This presents a challenge in making a comprehensive survey of work in the
 field.
 Some of the cases we are presenting have been found in very specific publicatio
ns; for example Joel Deshaye and Peter Stoicheff and their works on Faulkner's
 visualizations (cases 11, 12 and 13).
 Reading Stoicheff's notes it can be seen that they developed the tools
 just to assist in a very specific study of William Faulkner's narrative
 time lines.
 There are no references to applications of these interesting ideas to other
 texts, suggesting that more works remain hidden in the depths of other
 fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Text visualization, as we argue in this document, can be considered a subfield
 of data visualization.
 Yet, the boundaries of the field are sometimes not clearly defined.
 This is the case of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:31Search-Clock-by"

\end_inset

, in which the text corpora is an enormous dataset of search engine queries.
 Can this dataset be considered a collection of texts if each of them is,
 in most cases, is only one or two words long? Is there a minimum length
 of a text to be considered as a text? We decided to treat this case as
 a collection of texts, short ones, but, ultimately, texts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important decision in this review has been the classification of the
 cases found.
 Since there are few papers that review text visualization tools, we referenced
 the classic data visualization reviews 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "shneiderman_eyes_1996"

\end_inset

 as well as new ones (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "collins2009docuburst"

\end_inset

).
 In these cases the classifications were based on tasks that the visualization
 tool can solve rather than on the explicit aspects of the visualization.
 This is why we decided to propose our own classification that, while far
 from perfect, is hopefully a useful approach to a classification based
 on visual features.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the list of insights and gaps we have found so far:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Single text visualization cases are applied mainly to literature.
 Literature is an unstructured text; apart from complex combinations of
 words it can have high levels of human abstraction and freedom of structures
 and experimentation.
 It might be more effective to apply visualization techniques to other kinds
 of texts with a more formal register and/or predefined style, such as legal
 texts, scientific papers, template based texts and communications, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We have found only one single/part text visualization case which is sequential
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:22Document-Arc-Diagrams"

\end_inset

).
 Most part text visualizations extract the essence of the text based on
 some criteria and the original sequence of the text is lost.
 Since sequential visualization tools have some advantages, it seems there
 is room to develop part visualization tools that maintain the original
 text sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Collection visualizations use methods that can be found in data visualization
 in general.
 This idea invites experimentation in bringing more standard data visualization
 methods and tools to the specific text visualization subfield.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Collections of aggregations is the category that has developed more specific
 designs and ideas.
 More work needs to be done in order to find some patterns in this kind
 of visualization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Open questions related to nature of texts to be faced during this research
 include: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How can we extract the human part of a text?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In some ways, text to bag-of-words is a 
\shape italic
machinification
\shape default
 of the text, a simplification.
 What are we loosing in this transformations?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When the intrinsic human part of a text matters? In which tasks can be important
 to extract it and show it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are really big questions that quickly go outside the scope of the
 project, as it is defined here.
 To talk about many of these things we would need to go in to textual analysis
 in literature, as well as computational linguistics, digital humanities
 among other fields.
 As these fields are related but not directly belonging to data visualization,
 we assume that this research project will require investigation in these
 fields in order to contextualize and understand the tasks and challenges
 in which data visualization can help.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And finally: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Why is it that most of reviewed cases older than five years are no longer
 on line? If these tools are no longer (or never have been) in use, we should
 question their effectiveness.
 We have not investigated how many are part of commercial software products
 and how many, after being published, are just forgotten.
 In any case it is questionable why some great ideas did not become new
 standards.
 Should this research study or contribute to fighting this tendency? This
 project aims to produce applications that will be adopted in some field
 or to solve some task for some group of users; but as these cases show,
 adoption is a significant challenge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We hope to answer these and other questions in the long and challenging
 journey of this practical research project.
\end_layout

